						               													<description>&amp;ldquo;Events have cast on our arms and hopes the gloomiest of shadows.&amp;rdquo; &amp;ndash;Jefferson Davis&amp;rsquo; diary entry about the fall of Fort Donelson and the surrender of nearly 15,000 Confederate soldiers.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Battle&amp;rsquo;s Shadow is an historical simulation of the battle fought on February 15, 1862 at Fort Donelson. The fort was a Confederate stronghold on the Cumberland River, and key to the rebels retaining control of Kentucky and Tennessee. General Ulysses S. Grant&amp;rsquo;s Army of the Tennessee and Admiral Andrew H. Foote&amp;rsquo;s ironclad gunboats had laid siege to the Confederate fort, trapping the Confederate Army of Central Kentucky. On the morning of February 15th the rebels launched a desperate attack in attempt to breakout. Can you do as well or better?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each copy of Battle's Shadow is composed of the following:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Two 11 by 17 inch map sheets&amp;#10;176 un-mounted, double-sided counters&amp;#10;8 pages of rules&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each turn in Battle&amp;rsquo;s Shadow represents one hour of time. Infantry and Cavalry units represent regiments (III) or battalions (II). A hex on the map is approximately 200 meters across. Battle's Shadow is designed by Paul Rohrbaugh and features graphics by Tim Allen.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
